==English==

===Etymology===
* First attested in the 1530's.
* From {{etyl|la}} {{term|accommodatus|accomodātus|lang=la}}, perfect passive participle of {{term|accommodo|accomodō|lang=la}}; {{term|ad|lang=la}} + {{term|commodo|commodō|make fit, help|lang=la}}; {{term|com|lang=la}} + {{term|modus||measure, proportion|lang=la}}. See {{term|mode}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ə.ˈkɒm.ə.ˌdɵɪt/}}
* {{audio|en-us-accommodate.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|accommodat|ing}}

# {{context|transitive|often|reflexive}} To render fit, suitable, or correspondent; to adapt; to conform; as, to '''accommodate''' ourselves to circumstances.
#: ''They '''accommodate''' their counsels to his inclination.''  -[[w:Joseph Addison|Joseph Addison]]
# {{transitive}} To bring into agreement or harmony; to [[reconcile]]; to [[compose]]; to adjust; to settle; as, to '''accommodate''' differences, a dispute, etc.
# {{transitive}} To provide housing for; to furnish with something desired, needed, or convenient; as, to '''accommodate''' a friend with a loan or with lodgings.
# {{transitive}} To do a favor or service for; to oblige; 
# {{transitive}} To show the correspondence of; to apply or make suit by analogy; to adapt or fit, as teachings to accidental circumstances, statements to facts, etc.; as, to '''accommodate''' prophecy to events.
# {{transitive}} To give consideration to; to allow for.
# {{context|transitive}} To contain comfortably; to have space for.
# {{context|intransitive|rare}} To adapt one's self; to be conformable or adapted; become adjusted.

